al factors in psychological development.\")\n##\n(\"entity\"<|>ANALYTICAL PSYCHOLOGY<|>EVENT<|>Analytical Psychology is a school of thought developed by Jung that emphasizes the collective unconscious, archetypes, and the process of individuation.\")\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>JUNG<|>FREUD<|>Jung initially followed Freud's theories but later developed his own school of thought, Analytical Psychology, due to disagreements with Freud's emphasis on infantile sexuality and the concept of libido as a general life energy. He formally broke away from Freud in 1913.<|>8\")\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>ADLER<|>FREUD<|>Adler initially followed Freud's theories but later developed his own school of thought, Individual Psychology, due to disagreements with Freud's emphasis on infantile sexuality. He believed that the primary driving force in child development was the striving for superiority rather than sexual impulses.<|>8\")\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>HORNEY<|>FREUD<|>Horney developed her own approach to psychoanalysis, emphasizing the role of social and cultural factors in personality development and neurosis, which diverged from Freud's emphasis on biological and sexual factors.<|>7\")\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>SULLIVAN<|>FREUD<|>Sullivan focused on interpersonal relationships and their impact on mental health, contributing to the development of interpersonal psychoanalysis, which diverged from Freud's emphasis on intrapsychic conflicts.<|>7\")\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>RANK<|>FREUD<|>Rank initially worked closely with Freud but later developed his own theories, particularly on the role of birth trauma in psychological development, which diverged from Freud's emphasis on the Oedipus complex and infantile sexuality.<|>7\")\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>JUNG<|>VIENNA<|>Jung traveled to Vienna to participate in discussions with Freud and other early psychoanalysts, contributing to the development of psychoanalytic theory.<|>6\")\n##\n(\"relationship\"<|>ADLER<|>VIENNA<|>Adler was part of the